  "guidance": [
    {
      "type": "Change From Last Year",
      "text": "Additional guidance",
      "typeKo": "전년 대비 변경사항",
      "textKo": "전년 대비 변경사항은 2026 CDP 원문 및 변경 추적표 기준으로 확인하십시오."
    },
    {
      "type": "Requested Content",
      "text": "General \nThis question requests the unique identifiers relevant to your organization at the parent level. Do not enter subsidiary unique identifiers here.\nUnique identifier (column 1) \nThis column uses a fixed row, add row combination. If your organization has more than one unique identifier, add rows as needed.\nProvide your unique identifier (column 3) \nThis column is only presented if \"Yes\" is selected in column 2 \"Does your organization use this unique identifier?\".\nEnsure that you enter the correct format for your unique identifier. For example, ISIN codes include a two-letter country code, followed by a nine-character alphanumeric identifier and a single check digit.\nIf providing an identifier for the row \"Other unique identifier\", specify the type of identifier as well as the identifier code.",
      "typeKo": "요청 내용",
      "textKo": "이 섹션은 해당 문항에서 CDP가 요청하는 작성 내용을 설명합니다. 위 응답방법, 열 구조, 드롭다운 선택지를 기준으로 보고연도와 조직 범위에 맞는 정보를 입력하십시오."
    },
    {
      "type": "Explanation of Terms",
      "text": "CUSIP number: Committee on Uniform Security Identification Procedures number, a 9-character alphanumeric code that identifies a security for the purposes of facilitating clearing and settlement of trades. CUSIPs are used to distinguish, among other reasons, between multiple share classes or bond tranches. CUSIPs are mostly used in the United States and Canada. \nD-U-N-S: Dun & Bradstreet Universal Numbering System, a system of nine-digit numerical identifiers assigned by Dun & Bradstreet to business entities. The D-U-N-S number is used to establish and maintain a standardized business profile and is widely used for business credit reports.\nISIN: International Securities Identification Number, a 12-character alphanumeric code used to identify a security, such as a stock or bond. It is structured with the first two letters referencing the country/area of origin of the issuer for the security, in accordance with ISO 3166. The second grouping consists of nine characters made up of digits and letters, which is the unique identifying code for the security. In the U.S. and Canada this is known as the CUSIP number (see below). The final digit is the check digit which ensures the authenticity of the code. \nLEI: Legal Entity Identifier, a 20-character code used to uniquely identify legally distinct entities that engage in financial transactions. \nSEDOL code: Stock Exchange Daily Official List code, a 7-character identification code consisting of two parts: a 6-character alphanumeric code and a trailing check digit. SEDOLs issued prior to January 26, 2004 were composed only of numbers. SEDOLs serve as the National Securities Identifying Number for all securities issued in the United Kingdom. \nTicker symbol: a ticker symbol, also known as a stock symbol, is a unique series of letters assigned to a security for trading purposes. Ticker symbols are usually related to the organization's name, and additional letters denote additional characteristics such as share class or trading restrictions.",
      "typeKo": "용어 설명",
      "textKo": "이 섹션은 문항에서 사용하는 주요 용어의 의미를 설명합니다. 용어 해석은 CDP 2026 원문과 국문 양식의 용어 사용을 우선 적용하십시오."
    }
  ],
